Part 3

The shelter ran on a different kind of math.

In the head office, Vikram had watched ledger entries balance down to the paisa.

Here, a sack of potatoes was expected to stretch for nine days, but occasionally stretched for eleven because Ramu's nephew brought three heads of cauliflower that had gone slightly soft at the edges.

Vikram's job was the water.

Every morning at five, before the trucks on the bypass started their high-pitch honking, he drew twelve buckets from the well.

The first six went to the kitchen.

The next four to the wash area behind the drums.

The last two he kept near the drumstick trees for the children.

His hands, which had gone soft from ten years of holding executive pens, grew a thin layer of yellow calluses along the base of the fingers.

"You're drawing too fast," Sarita told him one morning.

She was sitting on the steps of the verandah, using a piece of broken glass to scrape the dirt off a pair of old rubber sandals.

"The rope will slip," she said.

"The rope is new," Vikram said.

"Ropes don't care if they are new, Vikram. They slip when they are tired."

She went back to the sandals.

She looked tired herself. Her cheeks had gone slightly hollow over the last two weeks, her eyes carrying the grey shadow that came when the medicine from the government hospital didn't suit her stomach.

She never mentioned it.

But Vikram had started noticing the exact hour she went to her room to lie down.

It was always three in the afternoon, when the heat of the tiled roof was the worst.

---

Ananya sat on the well wall, her legs swinging over the side.

She was holding a notebook Vikram had bought from the bypass store.

"What is this word?" she asked, pointing her pencil.

"*Equation,*" Vikram said.

"What does it mean?"

"It means two sides have to be equal. What you put on the left must match what is on the right."

She thought for a moment, her pencil tip touching her lip.

"Like a balance scale?"

"Yes."

"But if you put something on one side, and the other side has nothing, what happens?"

"It tilts," Vikram said.

"Then it is not an equation."

"No."

She closed the notebook.

"The school had a big black board," she said. "The teacher had three colors of chalk. Yellow, pink, and white. She only used the pink one when someone got the answer wrong."

"Which color did she use for you?"

"White," Ananya said. "I didn't get answers wrong. I just had the bad blood."

She hopped off the wall.

"Let's make the tea. Ramu's nephew brought the ginger today."

---

The tea stall near the bypass was run by a man named Shankar.

He had one wooden bench that sat in the shade of a hoarding advertising cement.

Vikram and Ananya walked there in the evenings.

Not because the shelter tea wasn't enough.

Because Shankar's stall was the only place where the truck drivers and the local laborers sat together without asking who had what.

They sat on the wooden bench, their backs to the cement ad.

Shankar served the tea in small glass tumblers.

Red tea.

Strong, sweet with local jaggery, smelling of the dry mud of the roadside and the diesel exhaust of the passing carriers.

"Your brother came to the factory yesterday," Shankar said, wiping a glass with a dirty rag.

Vikram looked at the road.

A multi-axle truck carrying iron ore was moving slow, its gears groaning under the weight.

"Reddy garu was with him," Shankar continued. "They had three cars. The big white one."

"Rohan likes the white one," Vikram said.

"People say he is very strict. He fined two loaders for being ten minutes late."

Vikram took a sip of his tea.

The jaggery was burnt at the bottom, leaving a bitter, sweet crust on the glass.

Ananya was watching a puppy near the tire shop.

"Let him be strict," Vikram said. "A new house needs a strong door."

"But you," Shankar said, looking at Vikram's faded cotton shirt. "You were the Ahuja saab. People used to stand up when your car passed the crossing."

"They still stand," Vikram said. "To cross the road."

Shankar laughed.

He didn't ask further.

---

They walked back as the sun was setting behind the bypass hills.

The sky had gone the color of a bruised plum.

Ananya was walking ahead, balancing herself on the concrete edge of the drain.

"Vikram," she called.

"Yes."

"When the school starts again, will you teach me the pink chalk words?"

"Yes," Vikram said.

"Even the ones that are wrong?"

"Especially those."

She smiled, her plates swinging as she ran a few steps ahead.

At the shelter gate, the brick was still holding the iron grill open.

The smell of Ramu's nephew's wood fire was coming from the kitchen — dry wood, slightly damp from the evening dew, mixing with the smell of the red tea they had left behind at the bypass.

Vikram stood near the gate.

He looked at his hands.

The calluses were rough. The nails had grey dirt under them that didn't go away with well water.

But his chest felt light.

Like the air bubble trapped in the saline tube, he had finally found the lock, and it had opened.

He walked inside.

The red tea was waiting.

